escent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Rall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Bernhardt, Dieter, Fritz, Otto, Rainer, Reinhold.","German: nickname for a raucous or noisy individual, from Swabian <i>rallen</i> ‘to make noise, screech like a tomcat’.","English: from the Middle English (from Old French) personal name <i>Raul</i>, a common form of   Ralph  ."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Rose Ralls was born in 1385, in Felsham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with John Goodrich. She died in 1470, in her hometown, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1385–1470":"1385–1470","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1425–1475":"1425–1475","1425":"1425","1475":"1475","1385":"1385","1470":"1470","1380":"1380","1439":"1439","Felsham, Suffolk,  England":"Felsham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Felsham, Suffolk, England":"Felsham, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1385–1470":"1385–1470","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1425–1475":"1425–1475","1425":"1425","1475":"1475","1385":"1385","1470":"1470","1380":"1380","1439":"1439","Felsham, Suffolk, 